 Core scraping & extraction ()

Automatic gallery detection — detect common gallery patterns (tiles, lists, carousels) and surface candidate containers.

Manual selector mode (point-and-click) — overlay picker that returns tested CSS/XPath selectors for items and sub-elements.

Smart selector suggestions — heuristic engine that suggests best selector(s) after analyzing DOM (e.g., nth-child, attribute-based, data- attributes).

Multi-element extraction — scrape: thumbnail URL, full-size image URL(s), detail page URL, captions, alt text, surrounding metadata (date, author, id).

Support for <img> and CSS background-image — extract images referenced in markup or styles.

Detail-page follow — optionally open/fetch detail pages to extract higher-res assets or metadata.

Batch/detail scraping mode — Quick-scan (thumbnails only) and Deep-scan (follow details, fetch EXIF, captions).

2) Advanced download management ()

Native Chrome downloads API integration — use chrome.downloads for reliability where possible.

Advanced download features — implement comprehensive download management: filters, masks, queueing, concurrency, speed limits, segmented downloads where feasible.

Flexible export options — offer multiple download formats and integration capabilities for downloaded content.

Unified queue (internal + external) — maintain internal queue UI and show items sent to external downloader with sync status if possible.

Save-as mask & renaming — powerful filename mask system with tokens, counters, sanitization, conflict-resolution modes (overwrite/skip/uniquify), live preview.

Save path handling — best-effort folder naming; integrate with native messaging host (optional) for exact folder placement beyond browser limitations.

3) Queueing, concurrency & retries ()

Configurable concurrency — global + per-host concurrency limits.

Per-host throttling / rate-limiting — prevent hammering single domains (requests/sec, bytes/sec).

Retry logic with exponential backoff — configurable retry count and backoff parameters.

Pause / resume queue — persistent across UI refreshes; resume on new session when allowed.

Prioritization & re-order — move items to top, deprioritize, bulk reorder, and stickiness for failed priorities.

Granular progress reporting — per-item progress (bytes/percentage), overall queue progress and ETA calculation.

4) Resumable / segmented downloads 

Range request / segmented download support — use HTTP Range for large files and segmented concurrency for speed (respect server support).

Resume on interruption — resume partial downloads where server supports Range and browser APIs permit.

Fallback handling — auto-fallback to single-stream download when segmented download fails.

5) Filtering, selection & transformations ()

Filter rules (include/exclude) — by regex, MIME type, extension, size thresholds, width/height, domain/path patterns.

Deduplication rules — skip identical URLs, skip identical content (hashing), and filename-based dedupe.

Image validation — optional head-request or minimal payload fetch to verify MIME and content-length before full download.

Batch transforms — inline image conversions (optionally client-side: webp→jpg converter), stripping query strings, normalizing URLs.

6) Filename mask & export formats ()

Robust tokens — *name*, *ext*, *num*, *url*, *domain*, *subdirs*, *caption*, *date*, time tokens, and custom metadata fields.

Persistent counters & scoped counters — global and per-site counters that persist in storage.

Preview & test panel — show live previews and conflict resolution behavior for sample items.

Exports — JSON (full structured report), CSV, XLSX; saved logs with timestamp, summary, and item list.

7) Pagination & lazy-loading ()

Auto-pagination detection — next-link detection, numeric pagination detection, form-based pagination.

Infinite-scroll handling — automatic smart scrolling (IntersectionObserver, scroll+delay), sentinel detection, visible-area heuristics.

Configurable limits — max pages, max scroll attempts, stop conditions (no new items).

Circular pagination avoidance — detect loops and stop gracefully.

8) Authentication & session handling ()

Use browser session — operate within logged-in session cookies; content scripts should run in-page to access authenticated DOM.

Profile-based auth handling — store site profile notes for sites needing special flows (token refresh, JS triggers).

Credential safety — never request credentials; rely on browser session only; show guidance to user to log in before scraping.

9) Site profiles / recipes ()

Built-in profiles for common layouts — include pre-made site profiles (e.g., stock galleries, media agencies) with selectors and special rules.

Custom user profiles — allow saving/overriding selectors, pagination rules, and filename masks per domain.

Remote profile updates — optional fetch/update mechanism with local cache and manual import/export.

10) Selector toolbox & test harness ()

Selector tester — evaluate a selector on the active page, highlight matches, and show sample extracted fields.

CSS/XPath toggle — offer both styles for advanced users.

Fallback selector chain — define primary and fallback selectors for robustness.

11) UI / Dashboard / UX ()

Professional dashboard — clean two-column layout: controls/presets on left, live queue/logs/tabs on right.

Tabs — Items, Exports, Logs, Settings, Profiles.

Compact & expanded item cards — show thumbnail, source URL, destination filename, status, actions (retry, open, copy url).

Keyboard shortcuts — start/stop, open picker, focus search, etc.

Context-menu integration — right-click on page items or links to "Add to Download Queue" / "Add all images" actions.

Notifications — system notifications for completion/errors (configurable).

12) Automation & macros 

Macro recorder — record click/scroll/type flows (with waits) and replay across pages to navigate galleries that require interaction.

Conditional waits — wait for selector, URL change, or network idle.

Parameterized macros — macros that accept variables (e.g., start page index) for batch runs.

13) Reliability, performance & scale ()

Memory-efficient processing — stream/process items to avoid OOM on very large galleries (10k–100k items).

Worker threads — use Web Workers for CPU-intensive tasks (hashing, image processing).

Backpressure & queue spillover — avoid overloading memory by paging queue to disk (IndexedDB) or streaming.

Telemetry (opt-in) — anonymized crash/usage metrics, feature usage; strictly opt-in and GDPR-friendly.

14) Image hashing / dedupe advanced 

Perceptual hashing — average/hash algorithms (aHash, pHash) in worker threads to detect near-duplicates.

Hash tolerance config — set similarity thresholds to treat images as duplicates.

Duplicate reporting — show duplicate groups and allow bulk dedupe actions.

15) Advanced media support 

Video & streaming — detect direct mp4/webm and segmented streams (HLS m3u8) and offer appropriate download handling (m3u8 segment fetching + merge or handoff to external).

Multi-resource items — items with multiple sources (thumb + full + raw) should be grouped and optionally downloaded together.

Archive downloads — collect sets and optionally compress to ZIP in-browser or via serverless cloud action.

16) Cloud & external uploads ()

Direct upload targets — S3, Google Drive, Dropbox, FTP/SFTP, WebDAV as post-download actions.

Presets & connectors — store upload credentials/tokens securely (prefer OAuth where possible).

Upload retry & validation — checksum verification after upload.

17) Native host & filesystem integration ()

Native messaging host — optional native helper to allow absolute path writes, better folder selection, and faster streaming to disk.

Installer / native host for advanced users — provide signed native host installer for Windows/Mac/Linux.

18) Privacy, security & legality ()

Local-only by default — no server-side scraping unless explicitly enabled by user.

Explicit user warnings — copyright, terms-of-service, and automated scraping legal note in onboarding.

Respect robots.txt toggle — configurable: warn users when ignoring robots.txt and allow opt-in to obey it.

Least-privilege permissions — request only necessary extension permissions, explain why each is required on install.

Secure storage — encrypt sensitive tokens and only persist what is necessary.

19) Accessibility & localization 

A11y — keyboard navigation, ARIA labels, contrast compliance, and screen reader support.

i18n — localization-ready strings and pluralization; provide at least English + one other language as demo.

20) Testing, QA & CI ()

Unit tests — core libs (selector heuristics, mask parser, queue logic, dedupe).

Integration tests — use headless Chromium tests for scraping flows and downloads (mock responses).

End-to-end tests — test on representative sample sites (internal fixtures) to validate selectors & pagination.

Performance benchmarks — automated tests for large-gallery throughput, memory usage, and concurrency.

Security audits — static analysis and dependency checks.

21) Developer ergonomics & architecture ()

Modular architecture — clear separation: UI, content-scripts, background service worker, downloader module, profile store, worker pool.

TypeScript preferred — strong typing for robustness.

Well-defined APIs / messages — message contracts between content script and background with versioning.

Extensible plugin hooks — small plugin API for adding custom processors (e.g., site-specific processors).

Documentation — developer README, architecture diagram, onboarding for new devs.

